<section xml:id="gal-rep-eigen" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Galois Representations Associated to Eigenforms</title>
  <p>
    In this chapter we discuss Galois representations associated to eigenforms. Eigenforms are a special class of modular forms that have particularly nice properties and are closely related to Galois representations.
  </p>
  <p>
    Suppose <m>f \in S_k(N,\chi)</m> be a normalised simultaeneous eigenform:
    <me>
      f = \sum_{n = 1}^{\infty} a_n(f)q^n \:\:\:\:\: (q = e^{2 \pi i z})
    </me>
    where <m>a_(f) = 1</m> and <m>T_l(f) = a_l(f)f</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Our main goal is to explain
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\exists</m> a number field <m>K_f</m> such that <m>a_l(f) \in K_f, \:\: \forall l</m>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Fix <m>\overline{\mathbb{Q}} \hookrightarrow \overline{\mathbb{Q}}_p</m> for any prime <m>p</m>. Then <m>\exists</m> a continuous representation
          <me>
            \rho_{f,p} = \text{Gal}(\overline{\mathbb{Q}}/\mathbb{Q}) \to \text{GL}_2(\overline{\mathbb{Q}}_p)
          </me>
          where <m>\text{GL}_2(\overline{\mathbb{Q}}_p)</m> gets the topological group and <m>\text{Gal}(\overline{\mathbb{Q}}/\mathbb{Q})</m> is profinite, and hence get's the Krull topology, i.e this map is a continuous homomorphism of topological groups such that
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\rho_{f,p}</m> is unramified at all <m>l \nmid N_p</m>(action of inertia group at <m>l</m> is trivial)
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\text{det}\rho_{f,p}(\text{Frob}_l) = \chi(l)l^{k - 1}</m>; <m>l \nmid N_p</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\text{Tr}\rho_{f,p}(\text{Frob}_l) = a_l(f)</m>; <m>l \nmid N_p</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\rho_{f,p}</m> is irreducible.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>

  <subsection xml:id="review-inertia-frob">
    <title>Review of Inertia and Frobenius Actions</title>
    <p>
      In this subsection, we will review the concepts of Inertia group and Frobenius actions in the context of Galois representations. 
    </p>
    <p>
      Fix <m>\overline{\mathbb{Q}} \hookrightarrow \overline{\mathbb{Q}}_l</m>. We thus have <m>D_l = \text{Gal}(\overline{\mathbb{Q}}_l/\mathbb{Q}_l) \to \text{Gal}(\overline{\mathbb{Q}}/\mathbb{Q})</m>. Then we have the following exact sequence
      <me>
        1 \to I_l \to D_l \to D_l/I_l \cong \hat{\mathbb{Z}} \to 1
      </me>
      The topological generator of <m>D_l/I_l \cong \hat{\mathbb{Z}}</m> is called the Frobenius element and denoted by <m>\text{Frob}_l</m>. This gives a factorisation of the map <m>\text{Gal}(\overline{\mathbb{Q}}/\mathbb{Q}) \to \text{GL}_2(\overline{\mathbb{Q}}_p)</m>, hence talking about the Frobenius makes sense.
      
      
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <p>
    The above points <m>(1)</m> and <m>(2)</m> comes from connections between modular forms and geometry (more precisely cohomology). 
  </p>

  

</section>